# Chapter 15 — Sharing your Scheme

Fourteen chapters have been about *writing* Motoi Scheme.
Chapter 15 is about *shipping* it — publishing a cart to the
registry, signing it, versioning it, letting other people run it
in their shops. The language is enough by itself to make small
programs; the sharing layer is what turns those programs into
something the community can rely on.

The sharing shape has three pieces: a package format (what does a
cart look like on disk), a signature layer (who wrote it, is it
unmodified), and a registry (where does it live, how do you find
it). Motoi Scheme uses SLAT for all three — because a cart *is*
a SLAT record with an ed25519 signature over its Merkle root.

## The cart on disk

```scheme
;; example-cart.sks
;;~ name       inventory-low-watch
;;~ version    1.0.0
;;~ author     ed25519:1a2b3c...
;;~ tier       green
;;~ purpose    \"alert when any SKU drops below 5 units\"
;;~ signed-at  2026-07-12T14:30:00Z

(define (inventory-low? threshold)
  (filter
    (lambda (sku)
      (< (sku/current-units sku) threshold))
    (shop/all-skus)))

(define (alert-if-low)
  (let ((low (inventory-low? 5)))
    (unless (null? low)
      (sakura/say
        (string-append
          \"Heads up — \"
          (number->string (length low))
          \" SKUs below 5 units. Want the list?\")))))

(alert-if-low)
```

The header block (lines starting with `;;~`) is metadata. Every
cart carries a name, version, author, tier, and a one-line
purpose. Everything after is Scheme.

## Signing

The signing step happens outside the cart itself. A cart-signing
tool reads the file, computes a Merkle root over its content,
signs the root with the author's ed25519 key, and writes the
signature into the `;;~ signature` header.

```scheme
;; After signing:
;;~ name       inventory-low-watch
;;~ version    1.0.0
;;~ author     ed25519:1a2b3c...
;;~ signature  ed25519:9f8e7d...
;;~ merkle     sha256:c3d4e5...
;;~ signed-at  2026-07-12T14:30:00Z
```

Any consumer can verify the signature: recompute the Merkle root
over the cart body, verify the signature over that root using the
author's public key. If it verifies, the cart is unmodified since
the author signed it.

## The registry

The registry is a shared directory of published carts. In Sakura
Scheme's case, it's the Curator carts folder at
`curator-web/src/scheme/carts/<tier>/*.sks`. Each tier has its
own trust level:

```scheme
(define tier-trust
  '((white         . self-signed-fine)
    (pink          . self-signed-fine)
    (green         . self-signed-with-community-review)
    (light-purple  . requires-lacuna-labs-signature)
    (deep-purple   . requires-lacuna-labs-signature-and-review)))
```

Higher tiers require more scrutiny. Publishing at `white` is
free; publishing at `deep-purple` requires a review process and a
Lacuna Labs signature.

## Semantic versioning

Version bumps follow the shape everyone uses: `MAJOR.MINOR.PATCH`.
Breaking changes bump the major. New capabilities bump the minor.
Fixes bump the patch. A cart's signature is over its versioned
content — every version is a distinct signed artifact.

```scheme
(define (version-bump-shape old new)
  (cond
    ((different-signature-shape? old new)  'MAJOR)
    ((added-capability? old new)           'MINOR)
    ((only-fixed? old new)                 'PATCH)))
```

Consumers pin to a version or a version range; the pin means
\"give me this cart at this version, verify the signature, run it.\"

## Consumers running a shared cart

```scheme
;; Fetch and verify:
(define low-watch (cart/fetch 'inventory-low-watch \"1.0.0\"))
(cart/verify-signature low-watch)   ;; => #t or error

;; Run:
(cart/run low-watch '(:threshold 5))
```

The consumer never has to trust the wire — they trust the
signature. If the wire returns a modified cart, the signature
verification fails and the run refuses.

## Publishing your own

For a cart at the `white` or `pink` tier, publishing is a
one-command move:

```
sakura-cart publish ./inventory-low-watch.sks
```

The command signs with your local key, uploads to the registry,
returns the versioned URL. Others can now fetch by name+version.

For higher tiers, publishing goes through a review process —
carts at Dream ($40) and Magic ($100) tiers involve Lacuna Labs
signing and community review. That's not gatekeeping for its own
sake; it's a trust guarantee for consumers spending money to run
these carts on their shops.

## Sakura's register on shipping a cart

She encourages publishing. A shared cart is one that other people
can benefit from, and every publication grows the registry. She
also warns: read your cart before shipping. Once it's signed and
in the registry, other people may run it in their shops. The
signature is your accountability for what happens.

> **Sakura says**
>
> When you publish a cart, it stops being just yours. Other
> people might run it on their shops. Your signature is your
> promise that the cart does what its name says. Read it once
> more before you sign; you're accountable for what it does out
> there.

## Exercises

1. Write a cart that computes weekly revenue and add the full
   header block. Sign it (simulate the signing) and verify it.
2. Bump the version from 1.0.0 to 1.1.0 by adding a
   capability. What changed in the cart? What stayed?
3. Give a case where a cart's signature verification fails.
   What happens next — does the cart refuse to run, or run
   with a warning?
4. What's the difference between publishing at `white` tier and
   `green` tier? What accountability does each carry?
")
